Xi Jinping calls to make the economy more open to the world spinel
The economy should become more open to the whole world to spur its growth, as President Xi Jinping said on Tuesday in an address to the group, facing the task of banal leadership reforms.
"China should concentrate on attracting foreign investors and experts and develop a policy of openness," he said, addressing the participants of the 16th meeting of the Committee's central leading group for comprehensively deepening reform.
According to him, increasing openness and deepening reforms will give the economy a new impetus and vitality and provide new space for economic development.
The leading group adopted a number of directives, including the introduction of market access regulation for investors, changing the rules of border controls, the promotion of state-owned enterprises (SOE), attracting private capital and revising the registration system for residents.
According to the statement, it will draw up a list of sectors of economy and production, unavailable for investment.
The system will be gradually established through trial live programs.
This is an important step because it will give the market a bigger role in the allocation of resources, to ensure the legitimacy of the business sector and increase transparency, as it said in a statement.
The government will also weaken control of the powers granted to companies, thereby ensuring that companies themselves will conduct their business.
The statement also said that China will allow border regions to develop new models of cross-border economic cooperation and new mechanisms to strengthen local growth.
More areas will be made available to private investors in order to improve the openness of the state-dominated sectors of the economy.
"The government will not change its policy toward foreign investors and will protect the legitimate interests of companies with foreign financing, as well as to provide them with better conditions," the statement said.
It will also facilitate the procedure for submitting applications for permanent residence permits for foreigners, or "green card," by optimizing requirements and simplifying the process of filing.
The meeting also discussed ensuring the rights of lawyers and questions of training of professional judges and prosecutor's office workers.
According to an official report released after the meeting, it was also attended by Prime Minister Li Keqiang and ministers Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli.
